Sorted sequences Problem Code: ENDLE001
Submit (Practice)

A group of students wishes to separate a set of numbers into two sorted lists using stacks and queues. The steps of the developed algorithm are as follows:

Let there be an empty queue, say QQ, and an empty stack, say SS.

  1. If QQ is empty and SS is empty, then enqueue the first element xx into QQ.
  2. For the insertion of each element xx (other than first element), the following sequential process is designed.
    1. If element xx is greater than or equals to the rear element in QQ, then enqueue it in QQ.
    2. Else if SS is empty or element xx is less than or equals to the top element in SS, then push it in SS.
    3. Else
      1. Pop all the elements from SS and enqueue in QQ using the steps as given below:
        • If top element of SS is less than front element of QQ, then pop from SS and enqueue in QQ.
        • Else if top element of SS is greater than all the elements in QQ and QQ has elements in non-decreasing order, then pop from SS and enqueue in QQ.
        • Else if top element of SS is equal to the rear element in QQ, then pop from SS and enqueue in QQ.
        • Else dequeue from QQ and enqueue in QQ.
      2. Dequeue from QQ and enqueue in QQ till the front element of QQ is less than the element xx.
      3. Dequeue from QQ and push in SS.
      4. Push the element xx in SS.
      5. Dequeue from QQ and enqueue in QQ till the front element of QQ is greater than equals to the rear element in QQ.

Finally the contents of QQ and SS give the required sorted lists.

Input:

  • Line 1 contains an integer NN.
  • Line 2 contains space separated NN integers to be sorted.

Output:

Show the contents of QQ and SS (in separate lines) after each insertion. Nothing will be displayed if QQ or SS is empty.

Constraint:

  • All integers range in between 1 and 1000.

Sample Input I:

5
3 1 7 1 2

Sample Output I:

3 
3 
1 
3 7 
1 
3 7 
1 1 
1 1 7 
2 3

EXPLANATION I:

  • Insert 3. QQ and SS both are empty.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 3 (rear)
  • Insert 1. 1 is less than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 3. But SS is empty, so push 1 in SS.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 3 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 1
  • Insert 7. 7 is greater than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 3, so enqueue 7 in QQ.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 3 7 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 1
  • Insert 1. 1 is less than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 7. But 1 equals to the top element in SS, i.e. 1, so push 1 in SS.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 3 7 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 1 1
  • Insert 2. 2 is less than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 7. Also 2 is greater than the top element in SS, i.e. 1.
    1. So all the elements are popped from SS and enqueued in QQ.
      • 1 is less than 3. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 3 7 1 (rear)' and StackStack will be '1'.
      • 1 is less than 3. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 3 7 1 1 (rear)' and StackStack will be empty.
    2. If front of QQ is less than the element xx, then dequeue from QQ and enqueue in QQ.
      • 3 is greater than 2. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 3 7 1 1 (rear)' and StackStack will be empty. No change.
    3. Dequeue from QQ and push in SS. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 7 1 1 (rear)' and StackStack will be '3'.
    4. Push the element xx in SS.
      • So QueueQueue will be '(front) 7 1 1 (rear)' and StackStack will be '(top) 2 3'.
    5. If front of QQ is greater than the rear element in QQ, then dequeue from QQ and enqueue in QQ.
      • 7 is greater than 1. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 1 1 7 (rear)' and StackStack will be '(top) 2 3'.
    Therefore the output will be
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 1 7 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 2 3

Sample Input II:

8
1 4 3 5 8 7 2 6

Sample Output II:

1
1 4
1 4
3
1 4 5
3
1 4 5 8
3
1 3 4 5
7 8
1 3 4 5
2 7 8
1 3 4 5 6
2 7 8

EXPLANATION II:

  • Insert 1. QQ and SS both are empty.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 (rear)
  • Insert 4. 4 is greater than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 1, so enqueue 4 in QQ.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 4 (rear)
  • Insert 3. 3 is less than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 4. But SS is empty, so push 3 in SS.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 4 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 3
  • Insert 5. 5 is greater than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 4, so enqueue 5 in QQ.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 4 5 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 3
  • Insert 8. 8 is greater than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 5, so enqueue 8 in QQ.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 4 5 8 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 3
  • Insert 7. 7 is less than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 8. Also 7 is greater than the top element in SS, i.e. 3.
    1. So all the elements are popped from SS and enqueued in QQ.
      • 3 is greater than 1. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 4 5 8 1 (rear)' and StackStack will be '(top) 3'.
      • 3 is less than 4. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 4 5 8 1 3 (rear)' and StackStack will be empty.
    2. If front of QQ is less than the element xx, then dequeue from QQ and enqueue in QQ.
      • 4 is less than 7. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 5 8 1 3 4 (rear)' and StackStack will be empty.
      • 5 is less than 7. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 8 1 3 4 5 (rear)' and StackStack will be empty.
    3. Dequeue from QQ and push in SS. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 1 3 4 5 (rear)' and StackStack will be '8'.
    4. Push the element xx in SS.
      • So QueueQueue will be '(front) 1 3 4 5 (rear)' and StackStack will be '(top) 7 8'.
    5. If front of QQ is greater than the rear element in QQ, then dequeue from QQ and enqueue in QQ.
      • 1 is less than 5. So QueueQueue will be '(front) 1 3 4 5 (rear)' and StackStack will be '(top) 7 8'. No change.
    Therefore the output will be
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 3 4 5 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 7 8
  • Insert 2. 2 is less than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 5. But 2 is less than the top element in SS, i.e. 7, so push 2 in SS.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 3 4 5 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 2 7 8
  • Insert 6. 6 is greater than the rear element in QQ, i.e. 5, so enqueue 6 in QQ.
    • QueueQueue: (front) 1 3 4 5 6 (rear)
    • StackStack: (top) 2 7 8
All submissions for this problem are available.
